      "content": "That's a classic issue. It's likely due to the fact that in Python, the default behavior for the `range()` function is to stop one number short of the end value. So, when you do `for row in range(rows):`, it's actually stopping at `rows - 1`, not `rows`. You can fix this by using `range(rows)` instead. Alternatively, you can use `enumerate` to get both the index and the value, which will avoid this issue altogether.",
